Reading existing resources with Data sources
---------------------------------------------

DATA BLOCK : 
Data blocks allow teraform to access info abt existing resources rather than creating new ones.

Access Existing Infrastructure
-------------------------------
Retrieve the details of existing resources so they can be transferred in other terraform blocks.

Dependency Resolution
----------------------
Data blocks help when one resource relies on the properties of another existing resource.

Avoid Hardcoding Values
-----------------------
Data blocks prevents the need for hardcoded values by dynamically pulling in details, which makes configurations more adaptable.

data "aws_vpc" "prd" {
  filter {
    name = "tag:Name"
    values = ["prd-vpc"]
  }
}
resource "aws_subnet" "pub" {
  vpc_id = data.aws_vpc.prd.id
  cidr_block = "10.0.0.1/24"
}
output "prd_vpc_subnet" {
  value = data.aws_vpc.prd.cidr_block
}

Referencing data blocks :
------------------------
data blocks retrieve a wide range of info abt the specified resource -called attributes.
Data block attributes are referenced just like resource attributes: data.<type>.<name>.<attribute>
      data.aws_vpc.prd.arn
      data.aws_vpc.prd.id
      data.aws_vpc.prd.cidr_block
      data.aws_vpc.prd.owner_id
      
Parameterizing configurations with input variables
---------------------------------------------------
The problem : hardcoding values in tf
The solution : using VARIABLES in terraform
use different variable files but same tf config file

Variable block: 
A variable block is used to define inputs that can be reused and customized, making your configurations more flexible and dynamic. Variables allow u to parameterize
values instead of hardcoding them directly into resource blocks.
This approach improves reusability, simplifies managing multiple env and helps maintain cleaner, more maintainable configurations.

variable "vpshere-dc " {
  description = "Name of datacenter"
  type  = string
  default = "prd-workload-dc"
}
variable "vsphere-networks" {
  description = "list of networks"
  type = list(string)

  default = [
      "VM Network"
      "Management Network"
  ]
}

TYPES OF VARIABLES : 
-------------------
Primitive variable types: 
    ----string, number and bool

Complex Variable Types:
    ----List : A sequence of similar values. Presented by a pair of square brackets containing a comma-separated sequence of values.
              list start at 0.
              variable "permitted_size" {
                type = list
                default = ["t3.small", "t4g.micro"]
              }
  -----MAP : A group of values identified by named labels. series of key=value pairs.
             variable "course_details" {
                description = "course details"
                type = map(string)
                default = {
                  instructor = "bryan"      //var.course_details.instructor
                  course   = "terraform"    //var.course_details.course
                }
            }

  -----SET : A collection of guranteed unique values. Terraform does not support accessing elements of a set using an index because sets are unordered collections.
            note: Convert to a list to access.
           variable "pub_subnet_ids" {
              type = set(string)
              default = ["subnet-12345", "subnet-7654"]
           }

Referencing a Variable :  by using a name of the variable
  var.vpshere_dc
  var.vpshere_networks[0] //list




















